Introduction:This campaign calls for the recognition of the human RIGHT TO KNOW by the United Nations. It is crucial to know how and why governments make decisions that affect human rights and freedoms. Governments have to be held accountable and they should provide information accurately and thoroughly without any prior request by the citizenry. Although Freedom of Information Acts (FOIAs) provide citizens with the right to access to certain types of information, their application is overall patchy and inadequate.  Fifty years after the end of World War II, the ‘90s sparked fervent hope in the worldwide affirmation of human rights and democracy for all. At the turn of the millennium, such hopes rapidly vanished the ideals of a universal application of human rights and a democratic rule of law have crushed in most if not all established democracies.We believe it is not too late to turn the table around. A stern return to the Universal Declaration of Human Rights and the democratic Rule of Law can avoid the looming disaster ahead of us. And we need your help.The results of our analysis, based on a decade of research and political action, confirms the thesis formulated by Professor Deirdre Curtin in her critique of the democratic deficit in the European Union. Public debate in democratic societies is increasingly reduced to a consideration of today’s “emergency” issues. In an era of unlimited communication possibilities, little to no room is left for profound studies and debates on causes and long-term effects. Instead, modern media theorems dictate a regime where public opinion is fed a constant flow of pro and contra propositions on the extremes of both sides of the debate. Distracted by the noise of these emergencies, information on other decisions being taken are kept away from the public eye and from the parliamentary floor as well. When today’s citizens in a democratic society are not fully enjoying their democratic rights by participating in public debate, the rights of others around the world are at stake.Over the last two decades, the world has witnessed an increase in terrorist attacks and augmented and use of military capabilities in the name of national security, against the threats from terrorism, immigration, drugs. Victims of the multifaceted Reason of State are human rights, democratic accountability, lack of monitoring in the decision-making process, and peace. The RULE OF LAW is increasingly replaced by the Rule of Law Enforcement.We propose an antidote that seeks to complete, as was the original function in 1948, the human rights framework of freedom of expression and the right to seek and impart information in a democratic society: the recognition of the human RIGHT TO KNOW by the United Nations. It is crucial to know how and why governments make decisions that affect human rights and freedoms. A properly enforced right to know would improve the relationship between elected officials and voters and foster the development of the democratic rule of law. Governments have to be held accountable and they should provide information accurately and thoroughly without any prior request by the citizenry.It is YOUR human right to know. What we have done so far:- Published two books "Reason of State vs Rule of Law" and "SOS Rule of Law";- Created the "Global Committee for the Rule of Law", which is lobbying MPs and governemnt officials to support our proposal; - Produced the study "Unlocking the right to know" on the existing literature on the Right to Know so far; - Held a First International Conference in Brussels at the European Parliament and European Commission, 18-19 February 2014 available here;- Convened public meetings at:    - UN Human Rights Council, Geneva, 18 Sep 2014, watch here;   - House of Commons, London, 22 Oct 2014, listen here;   - Chamber of Deputies, Rome, 4 Dec 2014, watch here;   - Institute of Philosophical Studies, Naples, 19 January 2015, watch here;   - Senate of France, Paris, 30 March 2015, watch here;- Held a Second  International Conference at the Senate of the Republic, Rome, "Universality of human rights for the transition towards the Rule of Law and the affirmation of the Right to Know", 27 July 2015, watch here;- Held an International round-table at the UN Human Rights Council, Geneva, 13 May 2016, with Permanent Representatives of: Italy, Ireland, Morocco, Mexico, Canada. Watch here;- Held an international technical seminar at the Senate of the Republic, Rome, 29 November 2016, watch here; 
 

 
With your help we can:
· MEET Member States Representatives at the United Nations Human Rights Council in Geneva and at the United Nations in New York;
· RUN a public awareness campaign, through meetings, seminaries, articles, radio programmes;
· SPREAD the appeal for the Right to Know;
· ORGANIZE follow-up activities to be undertaken at the UN, including meetings with officials and NGOs representatives, side-events, press conferences;
· FEED our online platform www.globalcommitteefortheruleoflaw.org
The right to know is a tenet of the rule of law, that is why we propose a formal, universal recognition of the human and civil “Right to Know” how and why governments make decisions at different levels. We do not want to abolish State Secrecy, but limit its use and abuse by revising and enhancing existing mechanisms of democratic oversight to enable the advancement of a democratic, national and international Rule of Law. We need to gather more support from citizens, and experts in the fields of human rights and international law. 
We have come a long way.
We can't stop now.
PLEASE DONATE
 

Our team:
Nonviolent Radical Party Transnational and Transparty (NRPTT) is a political organisation – with General Consultative Status at the United Nations Economic and Social Council (ECOSOC) – promoting the application and respect of Human Rights and the Rule of Law. The NRPTT has participated in the work of various UN bodies on matters related to the promotion of civil and political rights; the support of bilateral and multilateral actions for the promotion of democracy in the world; the support of the activities of the ad hoc Tribunals for the Former Yugoslavia and for Rwanda; the establishment of the International Criminal Court; the adoption of the resolution for a moratorium on capital executions by the UN General Assembly; the promotion of an international ban on female genital mutilations.
Global Committee for the Rule of Law - Marco Pannella (GCRL) is a no-profit organization founded by the late Marco Pannella, leader of NRPTT. It is tasked specifically with promoting the rule of law through the initiative for the recognition of the right to know at the United Nations. 
Hands Off Cain (HOC) is a no-profit organization founded in 1994 advocating the gradual abolition of the death penalty worldwide through the promotion of a UN moratorium on capital executions.
